WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.324 align:middle line:90%


00:00:05.324 --> 00:00:08.810 align:middle line:84%
>> Is there a deeper, more
hidden esoteric meaning behind

00:00:08.810 --> 00:00:10.820 align:middle line:84%
the Hollywood films that
we all have to watch?

00:00:10.820 --> 00:00:11.465 align:middle line:90%
I'm Jay Dyer.

00:00:11.465 --> 00:00:12.485 align:middle line:90%
>> And I'm Jay Weidner.

00:00:12.485 --> 00:00:14.250 align:middle line:90%
And this is Hollywood Decoded.

00:00:14.250 --> 00:00:24.964 align:middle line:90%


00:00:24.964 --> 00:00:29.030 align:middle line:84%
>> Chinatown is Roman Polanski
trying his hand at neo-noir,

00:00:29.030 --> 00:00:32.509 align:middle line:84%
and what he does is tell a very
seedy tale about corruption

00:00:32.509 --> 00:00:35.660 align:middle line:84%
and degeneracy at the highest
levels of the Los Angeles

00:00:35.660 --> 00:00:36.780 align:middle line:90%
elite.

00:00:36.780 --> 00:00:38.613 align:middle line:84%
So that's what we're
going to look at today.

00:00:38.613 --> 00:00:41.840 align:middle line:84%
>> I think that Chinatown
really was a great throwback

00:00:41.840 --> 00:00:45.980 align:middle line:84%
to the '30s, which is a very
interesting time in Hollywood,

00:00:45.980 --> 00:00:50.540 align:middle line:84%
in L.A., and the whole history
of the Water Wars and William

00:00:50.540 --> 00:00:52.720 align:middle line:90%
Mulholland and all of that.

00:00:52.720 --> 00:00:55.700 align:middle line:84%
What Chinatown is really
about, more than anything

00:00:55.700 --> 00:00:57.100 align:middle line:90%
else, is corruption.

00:00:57.100 --> 00:00:57.900 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:00:57.900 --> 00:01:04.489 align:middle line:10%
>> And the name Chinatown
begins with a C, ends with an N,

00:01:04.489 --> 00:01:07.820 align:middle line:10%
and has the same exact number of
letters as the word corruption.

00:01:07.820 --> 00:01:11.750 align:middle line:84%
So it is the word they're
slipping in to the movie.

00:01:11.750 --> 00:01:13.850 align:middle line:84%
And every time they
use the word Chinatown,

00:01:13.850 --> 00:01:15.320 align:middle line:84%
they're talking
about corruption.

00:01:15.320 --> 00:01:17.480 align:middle line:84%
Like, I used to be
with him when we'd

00:01:17.480 --> 00:01:20.030 align:middle line:84%
patrol the streets of
Chinatown, implying

00:01:20.030 --> 00:01:22.730 align:middle line:84%
that Jack Nicholson
and the cop were once

00:01:22.730 --> 00:01:24.890 align:middle line:90%
corrupted cops on the street.

00:01:24.890 --> 00:01:27.230 align:middle line:84%
And there's literally no
doubt that Jack Nicholson

00:01:27.230 --> 00:01:29.300 align:middle line:90%
was probably a corrupted cop.

00:01:29.300 --> 00:01:32.420 align:middle line:84%
And so when the
ending-- the final

00:01:32.420 --> 00:01:35.780 align:middle line:84%
takes place in Chinatown where
Faye Dunaway is assassinated

00:01:35.780 --> 00:01:38.295 align:middle line:84%
by the police, that is the
ultimate in corruption.

00:01:38.295 --> 00:01:39.095 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:01:39.095 --> 00:01:42.770 align:middle line:84%
>> And her father doesn't
even care about her at all,

00:01:42.770 --> 00:01:44.960 align:middle line:84%
just wants to know if
the daughter is OK.

00:01:44.960 --> 00:01:48.740 align:middle line:84%
And the other thing about
Chinatown, which I really like,

00:01:48.740 --> 00:01:50.980 align:middle line:90%
is the sparseness of the style.

00:01:50.980 --> 00:01:53.600 align:middle line:10%
Polanski is not getting
in front of the story

00:01:53.600 --> 00:01:56.120 align:middle line:10%
with his camera, which
a lot of filmmakers

00:01:56.120 --> 00:01:58.090 align:middle line:10%
will grab a really
good script and then

00:01:58.090 --> 00:02:01.520 align:middle line:10%
ruin it by having too many
cuts, and kind of crazy camera

00:02:01.520 --> 00:02:02.570 align:middle line:10%
angles, and all that.

00:02:02.570 --> 00:02:06.895 align:middle line:84%
Polanski keeps his
style very, very 1930s,

00:02:06.895 --> 00:02:08.770 align:middle line:84%
as if he was making a
film in the '30s, where

00:02:08.770 --> 00:02:10.699 align:middle line:90%
the cameras were 400 pounds.

00:02:10.699 --> 00:02:13.190 align:middle line:10%
It took 15 minutes to
take even a little move.

00:02:13.190 --> 00:02:15.560 align:middle line:10%
They could barely
pan the cameras.

00:02:15.560 --> 00:02:19.530 align:middle line:84%
There's very little activity
going on in the movie.

00:02:19.530 --> 00:02:22.710 align:middle line:84%
And I think that that really
helps the story unfold.

00:02:22.710 --> 00:02:25.550 align:middle line:84%
And the story itself
is an amazing story.

00:02:25.550 --> 00:02:29.000 align:middle line:84%
There's nothing, in fact, more
interesting in American history

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:33.652 align:middle line:84%
than the corruption that
built Southern California.

00:02:33.652 --> 00:02:34.580 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah, exactly.

00:02:34.580 --> 00:02:37.330 align:middle line:84%
>> The people coming
in from New York.

00:02:37.330 --> 00:02:42.740 align:middle line:84%
First, the orange grove growers,
the farmers, and then they

00:02:42.740 --> 00:02:46.880 align:middle line:84%
steal the water, and then that
creates a viable atmosphere

00:02:46.880 --> 00:02:48.920 align:middle line:90%
for Hollywood to exist.

00:02:48.920 --> 00:02:53.570 align:middle line:10%
And you watch this town
grow from 45,000 people

00:02:53.570 --> 00:02:55.940 align:middle line:10%
at the beginning
of the 20th century

00:02:55.940 --> 00:02:59.580 align:middle line:10%
to millions to the second
biggest city in America

00:02:59.580 --> 00:03:01.520 align:middle line:10%
by the time we get to the '70s.

00:03:01.520 --> 00:03:04.580 align:middle line:84%
And the whole story
of Los Angeles

00:03:04.580 --> 00:03:09.320 align:middle line:84%
is encapsulated in Chinatown
in that it is all corrupt.

00:03:09.320 --> 00:03:13.390 align:middle line:84%
The beginnings of L.A. itself
were just massive corruption.

00:03:13.390 --> 00:03:17.330 align:middle line:10%
And so the whole
idea that corruption

00:03:17.330 --> 00:03:20.950 align:middle line:10%
is what built Hollywood,
corruption is what built L.A.,

00:03:20.950 --> 00:03:23.405 align:middle line:10%
is really at the
crux of this movie.

00:03:23.405 --> 00:03:25.760 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah, I love the setting--

00:03:25.760 --> 00:03:30.590 align:middle line:84%
this repackaging of the Dashiell
Hammett, James Ellroy-type

00:03:30.590 --> 00:03:34.940 align:middle line:84%
story, with the figure of
William Mulholland, who

00:03:34.940 --> 00:03:38.840 align:middle line:84%
represents the highest level
of corruption at the top.

00:03:38.840 --> 00:03:42.022 align:middle line:84%
So a lot of people have
this naive assumption

00:03:42.022 --> 00:03:43.730 align:middle line:84%
that, well, you can
just go to the police

00:03:43.730 --> 00:03:45.030 align:middle line:90%
and have your problems solved.

00:03:45.030 --> 00:03:47.180 align:middle line:84%
And the moral of
this whole story

00:03:47.180 --> 00:03:49.892 align:middle line:90%
is that the police are owned.

00:03:49.892 --> 00:03:51.350 align:middle line:84%
And we see so many
films even after

00:03:51.350 --> 00:03:53.660 align:middle line:84%
that that are inspired by
Chinatown that, I think, do

00:03:53.660 --> 00:03:56.870 align:middle line:84%
a good job of representing
this storyline like LA

00:03:56.870 --> 00:04:00.950 align:middle line:84%
Confidential or Black
Dahlia by Brian De Palma.

00:04:00.950 --> 00:04:03.605 align:middle line:84%
And it's a theme that
constantly pops up

00:04:03.605 --> 00:04:05.480 align:middle line:84%
but not one that we've
really touched on yet.

00:04:05.480 --> 00:04:09.710 align:middle line:84%
And there's also hints at
kind of the esoteric occult

00:04:09.710 --> 00:04:12.157 align:middle line:84%
aspects in the background
of these elite,

00:04:12.157 --> 00:04:14.240 align:middle line:84%
degenerate characters,
too, which we'll especially

00:04:14.240 --> 00:04:18.250 align:middle line:84%
see when we talk about Hodel
and Black Dahlia and things

00:04:18.250 --> 00:04:19.050 align:middle line:90%
like that.

00:04:19.050 --> 00:04:24.050 align:middle line:84%
But for me, I think what's
fascinating is the fact that

00:04:24.050 --> 00:04:27.770 align:middle line:84%
if you look at the time period
when you had a lot of public

00:04:27.770 --> 00:04:32.390 align:middle line:84%
works projects going-- like the
Hoover Dam and the idea behind

00:04:32.390 --> 00:04:36.470 align:middle line:84%
the L.A. waterworks being this
public thing that then becomes

00:04:36.470 --> 00:04:40.640 align:middle line:84%
privatized, it requires a lot of
skullduggery and almost a kind

00:04:40.640 --> 00:04:42.300 align:middle line:90%
of false flag that--

00:04:42.300 --> 00:04:43.100 align:middle line:90%
>> It does--

00:04:43.100 --> 00:04:46.700 align:middle line:84%
>> --that Mulholland organizes
in the storyline that leads

00:04:46.700 --> 00:04:49.160 align:middle line:84%
to the privatization where he's
going to control the water.

00:04:49.160 --> 00:04:52.460 align:middle line:84%
And we see this today with
these giant corporations

00:04:52.460 --> 00:04:55.170 align:middle line:84%
are going to say, wait, we own
all the water in this region.

00:04:55.170 --> 00:04:55.970 align:middle line:90%
>> Nestle.

00:04:55.970 --> 00:04:57.645 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah, we own the water.

00:04:57.645 --> 00:04:59.550 align:middle line:10%
>> Yeah, and the
false flag of course,

00:04:59.550 --> 00:05:04.220 align:middle line:10%
that begins Chinatown is a fact
that Mulwray, who's Mulholland,

00:05:04.220 --> 00:05:06.860 align:middle line:10%
he's dumping water at
night to make it look like

00:05:06.860 --> 00:05:09.440 align:middle line:10%
there's a water shortage when
there is no water shortage.

00:05:09.440 --> 00:05:10.190 align:middle line:10%
>> The control of
resources, exactly.

00:05:10.190 --> 00:05:10.990 align:middle line:10%
>> That's right.

00:05:10.990 --> 00:05:13.490 align:middle line:10%
And so he's creating a
false water shortage,

00:05:13.490 --> 00:05:16.910 align:middle line:10%
killing the farmers,
which is avidly

00:05:16.910 --> 00:05:22.770 align:middle line:10%
displayed in the courtroom
scene, and then draining--

00:05:22.770 --> 00:05:26.610 align:middle line:10%
literally draining the
rest of all of this water

00:05:26.610 --> 00:05:29.490 align:middle line:10%
down into L.A., sucking
the entire West dry.

00:05:29.490 --> 00:05:32.490 align:middle line:84%
And we know this is true because
the Owens Valley is losing

00:05:32.490 --> 00:05:34.290 align:middle line:84%
all of its water,
there are lakes

00:05:34.290 --> 00:05:36.660 align:middle line:90%
drying up all over California--

00:05:36.660 --> 00:05:39.120 align:middle line:84%
all hooked into this
gigantic aqueduct,

00:05:39.120 --> 00:05:42.360 align:middle line:84%
which is feeding Los Angeles,
which gets very little rain--

00:05:42.360 --> 00:05:44.880 align:middle line:84%
like eight or nine
inches a year of rain.

00:05:44.880 --> 00:05:47.550 align:middle line:84%
And so you see this
kind of giant sucking--

00:05:47.550 --> 00:05:51.780 align:middle line:84%
like almost Arconic
thing happening.

00:05:51.780 --> 00:05:54.030 align:middle line:84%
We're going to take all
the resources of the West

00:05:54.030 --> 00:05:55.485 align:middle line:84%
and turn it into
Hollywood movies.

00:05:55.485 --> 00:05:57.215 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah, right, exactly.

00:05:57.215 --> 00:05:59.000 align:middle line:90%
>> It's so crazy.

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:06.390 align:middle line:84%
>> And he has that name
that then becomes so iconic

00:06:06.390 --> 00:06:09.746 align:middle line:84%
for famous roads like
Mulholland Drive.

00:06:09.746 --> 00:06:11.370 align:middle line:84%
And you know, we
think of all the dark,

00:06:11.370 --> 00:06:12.996 align:middle line:84%
mysterious,
nefarious things that

00:06:12.996 --> 00:06:14.370 align:middle line:84%
have happened on
Mulholland drive

00:06:14.370 --> 00:06:17.807 align:middle line:84%
related to the Manson case,
and with Wonderland Avenue,

00:06:17.807 --> 00:06:19.140 align:middle line:90%
and Laurel Canyon, and all that.

00:06:19.140 --> 00:06:20.931 align:middle line:84%
What we're going to
look at first, I think,

00:06:20.931 --> 00:06:24.990 align:middle line:84%
is this scene that details this
elite privatization combined

00:06:24.990 --> 00:06:26.782 align:middle line:84%
with just total
psychopathy and degeneracy.

00:06:26.782 --> 00:06:27.581 align:middle line:90%
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

