00:18:57.070 --> 00:19:00.290 align:middle line:84%
and right after Rosemary's Baby,
his wife was killed by the--

00:19:00.290 --> 00:19:01.090 align:middle line:90%
>> Sharon Tate.

00:19:01.090 --> 00:19:03.700 align:middle line:10%
>> --yeah, Sharon Tate was
killed by the Manson family,

00:19:03.700 --> 00:19:04.850 align:middle line:10%
supposedly.

00:19:04.850 --> 00:19:07.185 align:middle line:84%
And again, there's
ties to ritualism--

00:19:07.185 --> 00:19:07.985 align:middle line:90%
>> Absolutely.

00:19:07.985 --> 00:19:11.330 align:middle line:84%
>> --Satanism being practiced
up in the Hollywood Hills,

00:19:11.330 --> 00:19:14.780 align:middle line:84%
the fact that he made a movie
about Satanism just previous

00:19:14.780 --> 00:19:17.750 align:middle line:84%
to this is a very odd
coincidence, I think.

00:19:17.750 --> 00:19:20.360 align:middle line:84%
>> Yeah, what's fascinating
is that this is neo-noir,

00:19:20.360 --> 00:19:23.390 align:middle line:84%
and the whole genre of noir,
as we said before in other

00:19:23.390 --> 00:19:26.422 align:middle line:84%
episodes, is very
influenced by surrealism.

00:19:26.422 --> 00:19:28.130 align:middle line:84%
And one of the most
prominent surrealists

00:19:28.130 --> 00:19:30.260 align:middle line:84%
was Man Ray-- that
very bizarre artist

00:19:30.260 --> 00:19:32.900 align:middle line:84%
who self-described
as a Luciferian.

00:19:32.900 --> 00:19:34.760 align:middle line:84%
And Man Ray was
believed to be connected

00:19:34.760 --> 00:19:37.229 align:middle line:84%
to the circles of
the Black Dahlia.

00:19:37.229 --> 00:19:39.770 align:middle line:84%
I mean, he was friends with John
Houston, friends with Hodel,

00:19:39.770 --> 00:19:42.140 align:middle line:84%
they all hung out, and partied,
and had orgies together,

00:19:42.140 --> 00:19:43.670 align:middle line:90%
according to the public record.

00:19:43.670 --> 00:19:45.440 align:middle line:84%
So yeah, I think
that we're looking

00:19:45.440 --> 00:19:50.900 align:middle line:84%
at a very dark background
that is maybe--

00:19:50.900 --> 00:19:52.430 align:middle line:84%
maybe Polanski's
films are his way

00:19:52.430 --> 00:19:55.580 align:middle line:84%
of trying to deal with
this-- kind of trying

00:19:55.580 --> 00:20:00.125 align:middle line:84%
to process all of this
darkness that he's been around.

00:20:00.125 --> 00:20:01.820 align:middle line:90%
>> I agree with that.

00:20:01.820 --> 00:20:04.280 align:middle line:84%
And in a way, a lot of it
is revelation of the method.

00:20:04.280 --> 00:20:05.090 align:middle line:84%
You know, that
they're are actually

00:20:05.090 --> 00:20:07.465 align:middle line:84%
showing us what goes down in
Hollywood in the background.

00:20:07.465 --> 00:20:08.300 align:middle line:90%
>> They are.

00:20:08.300 --> 00:20:11.840 align:middle line:84%
And again, I go back
to things that we've

00:20:11.840 --> 00:20:13.730 align:middle line:84%
touched on before
with the David McGowan

00:20:13.730 --> 00:20:15.320 align:middle line:90%
series on Laurel Canyon--

00:20:15.320 --> 00:20:17.720 align:middle line:84%
how this continued
into the '70s,

00:20:17.720 --> 00:20:21.020 align:middle line:84%
and how Polanski, during
the making of Chinatown,

00:20:21.020 --> 00:20:24.200 align:middle line:84%
must have been aware of
this secret studio that

00:20:24.200 --> 00:20:27.830 align:middle line:84%
was atop of Laurel Canyon and
all of the strange business

00:20:27.830 --> 00:20:30.410 align:middle line:84%
that was going on in
Laurel Canyon at the time.

00:20:30.410 --> 00:20:33.345 align:middle line:84%
And he lived in Laurel
Canyon with Sharon Tate,

00:20:33.345 --> 00:20:34.970 align:middle line:84%
and that's where the
murders took place

00:20:34.970 --> 00:20:37.280 align:middle line:90%
was at Roman Polanski's house.

00:20:37.280 --> 00:20:41.480 align:middle line:84%
And there's just so many
strange things going on

00:20:41.480 --> 00:20:44.630 align:middle line:84%
at that time period
that you really

00:20:44.630 --> 00:20:46.580 align:middle line:84%
have to zoom back
to get a bigger

00:20:46.580 --> 00:20:47.820 align:middle line:90%
picture of what's happening.

00:20:47.820 --> 00:20:50.600 align:middle line:84%
>> Yeah, one thing I think
that's interesting about

00:20:50.600 --> 00:20:54.410 align:middle line:84%
Polanski, as you said, is that
he's in these circles of all

00:20:54.410 --> 00:20:57.050 align:middle line:84%
these people who are involved
in a lot of this dark stuff.

00:20:57.050 --> 00:20:59.434 align:middle line:90%
So this is kind of his world--

00:20:59.434 --> 00:21:00.350 align:middle line:90%
for better or for ill.

00:21:00.350 --> 00:21:00.590 align:middle line:90%
>> That's right.

00:21:00.590 --> 00:21:02.730 align:middle line:84%
>> I mean, so the
artwork that he makes--

00:21:02.730 --> 00:21:05.480 align:middle line:84%
I think he's just putting
out there what he knows

00:21:05.480 --> 00:21:07.070 align:middle line:90%
and what he's seen.

00:21:07.070 --> 00:21:09.770 align:middle line:84%
And a lot of it is,
I think, bad stuff.

00:21:09.770 --> 00:21:10.570 align:middle line:90%
It's dark.

00:21:10.570 --> 00:21:12.722 align:middle line:84%
He tries to dress it up
and make it attractive,

00:21:12.722 --> 00:21:14.930 align:middle line:84%
especially when we look at
something like Ninth Gate.

00:21:14.930 --> 00:21:17.360 align:middle line:10%
But at times, he'll make
films that are very positive,

00:21:17.360 --> 00:21:19.420 align:middle line:10%
like Oliver Twist, which I
thought he did a good job at.

00:21:19.420 --> 00:21:20.450 align:middle line:10%
>> He did do a good job.

00:21:20.450 --> 00:21:20.720 align:middle line:10%
Great film.

00:21:20.720 --> 00:21:22.490 align:middle line:10%
>> So it's not always
bad with Polanski,

00:21:22.490 --> 00:21:29.780 align:middle line:10%
but what you have here is him
showing that the elite are

00:21:29.780 --> 00:21:32.510 align:middle line:10%
involved in the very
things that are illegal.

00:21:32.510 --> 00:21:34.354 align:middle line:84%
So the people that
run the police--

00:21:34.354 --> 00:21:36.770 align:middle line:84%
the police are the ones who
are supposed to be controlling

00:21:36.770 --> 00:21:37.700 align:middle line:90%
the vices, right?

00:21:37.700 --> 00:21:40.790 align:middle line:90%
The vice department.

00:21:40.790 --> 00:21:43.800 align:middle line:84%
They're owned by the
guys who own the vices.

00:21:43.800 --> 00:21:45.500 align:middle line:84%
And so I think that
he just sees it

00:21:45.500 --> 00:21:47.990 align:middle line:84%
as kind of a giant
contradiction, a giant game,

00:21:47.990 --> 00:21:48.982 align:middle line:90%
a giant absurdism.

00:21:48.982 --> 00:21:50.690 align:middle line:84%
Because he's partying
with all the people

00:21:50.690 --> 00:21:55.340 align:middle line:84%
who are buddies with the mayor,
and the governor of L.A.,

00:21:55.340 --> 00:21:57.770 align:middle line:84%
and that's who he
parties with, and he

00:21:57.770 --> 00:21:59.165 align:middle line:90%
sees what they're really doing.

00:21:59.165 --> 00:22:01.040 align:middle line:84%
So from his vantage
point, I think he sees it

00:22:01.040 --> 00:22:03.025 align:middle line:90%
as just giant contradictions.

00:22:03.025 --> 00:22:05.900 align:middle line:10%
>> Yeah, and again, like
you brought up Oliver Twist,

00:22:05.900 --> 00:22:06.980 align:middle line:10%
we are talking about--

00:22:06.980 --> 00:22:10.760 align:middle line:10%
he's still kind of
enthralled by the corruption,

00:22:10.760 --> 00:22:12.830 align:middle line:10%
even in a positive
movie like that.

00:22:12.830 --> 00:22:16.250 align:middle line:10%
He still wants to show you
the nugget of corruption

00:22:16.250 --> 00:22:18.500 align:middle line:10%
that destroys the boys' lives--

00:22:18.500 --> 00:22:20.270 align:middle line:10%
the pickpockets--
and I think he's

00:22:20.270 --> 00:22:22.820 align:middle line:10%
doing the same thing in
Chinatown, where he's trying

00:22:22.820 --> 00:22:24.790 align:middle line:10%
to show you the corruption.

00:22:24.790 --> 00:22:27.550 align:middle line:84%
But I think he is working
it out in some ways.

00:22:27.550 --> 00:22:29.690 align:middle line:84%
I think he feels maybe
a little bit ashamed

00:22:29.690 --> 00:22:33.090 align:middle line:84%
that he got accepted into
these big places and, you know,

00:22:33.090 --> 00:22:35.036 align:middle line:84%
the manipulation
that they're doing,

00:22:35.036 --> 00:22:36.660 align:middle line:84%
and I think he's
trying to work it out.

00:22:36.660 --> 00:22:38.940 align:middle line:84%
At the same time, he's
enthralled by it, I think.

00:22:38.940 --> 00:22:42.174 align:middle line:84%
>> Well, he probably was
the one who took the rap.

00:22:42.174 --> 00:22:44.340 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I don't imagine he
was the only person doing

00:22:44.340 --> 00:22:45.960 align:middle line:90%
illegal things in these circles.

00:22:45.960 --> 00:22:46.960 align:middle line:90%
>> I think you're right.

00:22:46.960 --> 00:22:49.170 align:middle line:84%
>> But he's the one
that ends up, you know,

00:22:49.170 --> 00:22:50.980 align:middle line:90%
banished to France, essentially.

00:22:50.980 --> 00:22:52.920 align:middle line:84%
I'm not saying that
he's good; I'm just

00:22:52.920 --> 00:22:54.330 align:middle line:84%
saying that that's
what happened,

00:22:54.330 --> 00:22:56.330 align:middle line:84%
historically-- he was
convicted of these things.

00:22:56.330 --> 00:23:00.210 align:middle line:84%
So I think that he's running
in these circles of people

00:23:00.210 --> 00:23:01.830 align:middle line:90%
who were--

00:23:01.830 --> 00:23:03.460 align:middle line:84%
he's making films
about corrupt people,

00:23:03.460 --> 00:23:05.085 align:middle line:84%
and if you're running
in those circles,

00:23:05.085 --> 00:23:07.170 align:middle line:84%
you have to expect that
you might get screwed over

00:23:07.170 --> 00:23:09.390 align:middle line:84%
by these corrupt people if
you're involved in their stuff.

00:23:09.390 --> 00:23:10.590 align:middle line:84%
>> And they were the
elite of Hollywood,

00:23:10.590 --> 00:23:12.256 align:middle line:84%
and they could get
anything they wanted,

00:23:12.256 --> 00:23:14.220 align:middle line:90%
and they acted that way.

00:23:14.220 --> 00:23:17.370 align:middle line:84%
>> So I think that even though
this is really dark imagery

00:23:17.370 --> 00:23:20.690 align:middle line:84%
and it's difficult, these are
culturally important films.

00:23:20.690 --> 00:23:22.920 align:middle line:84%
They're ranked by most
critics, by most academics,

00:23:22.920 --> 00:23:25.580 align:middle line:84%
by most film institutes, and
academies, as, you know--

00:23:25.580 --> 00:23:29.490 align:middle line:84%
this is usually even maybe in
the top 10 of American films.

00:23:29.490 --> 00:23:31.410 align:middle line:84%
So I think it's important
for that reason,

00:23:31.410 --> 00:23:33.000 align:middle line:90%
and we have to look at it--

00:23:33.000 --> 00:23:35.040 align:middle line:84%
we have to consider and
be aware of it, just

00:23:35.040 --> 00:23:37.360 align:middle line:84%
as a cultural
artifact, you know.

00:23:37.360 --> 00:23:40.506 align:middle line:84%
And in the same way that much
of Gothic literature that we

00:23:40.506 --> 00:23:41.880 align:middle line:84%
talked about was
very important--

00:23:41.880 --> 00:23:43.980 align:middle line:84%
Faulkner, Flannery
O'Connor, I mean,

00:23:43.980 --> 00:23:45.610 align:middle line:90%
these contain dark themes--

00:23:45.610 --> 00:23:47.040 align:middle line:90%
even, at times, Mark Twain.

00:23:47.040 --> 00:23:49.560 align:middle line:84%
But they're still important
for their significance--

00:23:49.560 --> 00:23:51.980 align:middle line:84%
for their symbolic
value and meaning.

00:23:51.980 --> 00:23:56.400 align:middle line:84%
And so even though we obviously
condemn the treatment of women,

00:23:56.400 --> 00:23:58.350 align:middle line:84%
I think Polanski's
showing us that that

00:23:58.350 --> 00:24:01.290 align:middle line:84%
was a period that was
brutal, and women were not

00:24:01.290 --> 00:24:02.220 align:middle line:90%
treated well then.

00:24:02.220 --> 00:24:06.227 align:middle line:84%
And so the extension
of rights to women

00:24:06.227 --> 00:24:08.310 align:middle line:84%
is something that's much
more positive in our day.

00:24:08.310 --> 00:24:11.220 align:middle line:84%
They have a lot more freedom
and rights than they had then,

00:24:11.220 --> 00:24:12.830 align:middle line:84%
and that's actually
a positive thing.

00:24:12.830 --> 00:24:13.630 align:middle line:90%
>> I agree.

00:24:13.630 --> 00:24:16.770 align:middle line:84%
And you know, I think
that Chinatown is slowly

00:24:16.770 --> 00:24:20.670 align:middle line:84%
climbing its way into the very
top echelon of best movies

00:24:20.670 --> 00:24:21.510 align:middle line:90%
ever made.

00:24:21.510 --> 00:24:24.180 align:middle line:84%
I think that's another reason
we had to include it in this.

00:24:24.180 --> 00:24:26.517 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it is
really a good movie.

00:24:26.517 --> 00:24:27.600 align:middle line:90%
There's no doubt about it.

00:24:27.600 --> 00:24:30.720 align:middle line:84%
I believe it's up there with
Vertigo, and Citizen Kane,

00:24:30.720 --> 00:24:34.170 align:middle line:84%
and 2001 as one of the
best films ever made.

00:24:34.170 --> 00:24:36.450 align:middle line:84%
And Polanski deserves
a lot of credit

00:24:36.450 --> 00:24:39.390 align:middle line:84%
for having the guts to
make a film like this.

00:24:39.390 --> 00:24:41.880 align:middle line:90%
So yes, it's hard to watch.

00:24:41.880 --> 00:24:45.000 align:middle line:84%
Yes, it's brutal in its honesty
about the way the world was

00:24:45.000 --> 00:24:47.880 align:middle line:84%
in the 1930s, especially
towards women,

00:24:47.880 --> 00:24:51.785 align:middle line:84%
and I think kudos to Polanski
for actually showing that.

00:24:51.785 --> 00:24:54.570 align:middle line:84%
>> Yeah, and I think we can
say that objectively about

00:24:54.570 --> 00:25:00.090 align:middle line:84%
a creation of art without making
a moral statement or a moral

00:25:00.090 --> 00:25:02.670 align:middle line:84%
promotion of the
person themselves.

00:25:02.670 --> 00:25:05.670 align:middle line:84%
I mean, we can condemn his
beliefs, and lifestyle,

00:25:05.670 --> 00:25:07.215 align:middle line:84%
and the actions that
he's committed--

00:25:07.215 --> 00:25:08.340 align:middle line:90%
>> And still like his film.

00:25:08.340 --> 00:25:10.620 align:middle line:84%
>> --and still appreciate
his artistic creation.

00:25:10.620 --> 00:25:11.420 align:middle line:90%
>> That's right.

00:25:11.420 --> 00:25:13.020 align:middle line:84%
I really think that
it's the art not

00:25:13.020 --> 00:25:14.945 align:middle line:90%
the artist that's important.

00:25:14.945 --> 00:25:18.120 align:middle line:84%
>> So I think that even
the darkest aspects

00:25:18.120 --> 00:25:22.230 align:middle line:84%
of our experience, they actually
serve a purpose in the grander

00:25:22.230 --> 00:25:24.900 align:middle line:84%
scheme or in Providence--
divine Providence or whatever--

00:25:24.900 --> 00:25:29.100 align:middle line:84%
to actually show us the reality
of the good and that the good

00:25:29.100 --> 00:25:31.590 align:middle line:84%
is actually stronger and
actually overcomes evil.

00:25:31.590 --> 00:25:32.540 align:middle line:90%
I firmly believe that.

00:25:32.540 --> 00:25:36.240 align:middle line:84%
And I think that even somebody
who is not a very respectable

00:25:36.240 --> 00:25:39.000 align:middle line:84%
character-- they're not totally
evil, so they're still--

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:40.590 align:middle line:84%
even in their
artwork, they're going

00:25:40.590 --> 00:25:42.780 align:middle line:84%
to have some aspect of
the good that comes out.

00:25:42.780 --> 00:25:45.750 align:middle line:84%
And I think that if
we look at Ninth Gate,

00:25:45.750 --> 00:25:48.270 align:middle line:84%
the film ends with
that same idea.

00:25:48.270 --> 00:25:50.460 align:middle line:84%
It's another Polanski
film that shows that even

00:25:50.460 --> 00:25:52.210 align:middle line:84%
in the midst of this
darkness, it actually

00:25:52.210 --> 00:25:55.230 align:middle line:84%
is something that leads
us back to the light

00:25:55.230 --> 00:25:58.470 align:middle line:84%
because darkness is
negation; it's privation,

00:25:58.470 --> 00:26:00.210 align:middle line:84%
as the ancient
philosophers used to say.

00:26:00.210 --> 00:26:01.200 align:middle line:90%
It's non-being.

00:26:01.200 --> 00:26:02.670 align:middle line:90%
It's nothingness.

00:26:02.670 --> 00:26:04.540 align:middle line:90%
And we crave existence.

00:26:04.540 --> 00:26:05.340 align:middle line:90%
We crave life.

00:26:05.340 --> 00:26:09.330 align:middle line:84%
We crave the fullness of being,
as Aristotle used to say.

00:26:09.330 --> 00:26:11.610 align:middle line:84%
So I think that if we
think about it that way,

00:26:11.610 --> 00:26:14.160 align:middle line:84%
it actually puts us back on
the road towards the good.

00:26:14.160 --> 00:26:20.360 align:middle line:84%
>> Yeah, I think that
uncovering darkness can lead you

00:26:20.360 --> 00:26:21.160 align:middle line:90%
to the light.

00:26:21.160 --> 00:26:22.890 align:middle line:90%
>> It tells us what to avoid.

00:26:22.890 --> 00:26:23.910 align:middle line:90%
>> What to avoid--

00:26:23.910 --> 00:26:27.390 align:middle line:90%
I often use the analogy of--

00:26:27.390 --> 00:26:30.790 align:middle line:84%
my generation went to Vietnam,
and when we came back,

00:26:30.790 --> 00:26:33.450 align:middle line:84%
we actually saw what
violence was really like.

00:26:33.450 --> 00:26:36.540 align:middle line:84%
And we began making movies
that depicted violence

00:26:36.540 --> 00:26:39.817 align:middle line:84%
as it really was, not a little
bullet hole going into someone,

00:26:39.817 --> 00:26:41.400 align:middle line:84%
a little blood coming
out, or anything

00:26:41.400 --> 00:26:42.780 align:middle line:90%
like that, it was real.

00:26:42.780 --> 00:26:45.600 align:middle line:84%
And we were criticized by
our parents' generation

00:26:45.600 --> 00:26:49.410 align:middle line:84%
as encouraging violence and
making it like it was OK.

00:26:49.410 --> 00:26:52.944 align:middle line:84%
But actually, people
watched those violent movies

00:26:52.944 --> 00:26:54.485 align:middle line:84%
and didn't want to
go to war anymore.

00:26:54.485 --> 00:26:55.285 align:middle line:90%
>> Exactly.

00:26:55.285 --> 00:26:57.270 align:middle line:84%
>> They didn't want to
be involved in violence,

00:26:57.270 --> 00:27:01.620 align:middle line:84%
which was really cool before the
violent movies and very uncool

00:27:01.620 --> 00:27:05.150 align:middle line:84%
at the other end of
the violent movies.

00:27:05.150 --> 00:27:07.840 align:middle line:84%
And I think Polanski
is revealing to us

00:27:07.840 --> 00:27:10.290 align:middle line:84%
the corruption that we really
didn't know about, even

00:27:10.290 --> 00:27:11.940 align:middle line:90%
in 1974.

00:27:11.940 --> 00:27:15.487 align:middle line:84%
And in that, we can see that we
have to make this world better.

00:27:15.487 --> 00:27:17.070 align:middle line:84%
We have to make sure
the elites aren't

00:27:17.070 --> 00:27:19.860 align:middle line:84%
doing this to their
children, and to us,

00:27:19.860 --> 00:27:21.292 align:middle line:90%
and make a better world.

00:27:21.292 --> 00:27:22.500 align:middle line:90%
And I think we actually have.

00:27:22.500 --> 00:27:24.459 align:middle line:84%
I think the world is
a better place now

00:27:24.459 --> 00:27:25.500 align:middle line:90%
than it was in the 1930s.

00:27:25.500 --> 00:27:29.700 align:middle line:84%
>> I think that if most people
have the false impression that

00:27:29.700 --> 00:27:33.620 align:middle line:84%
if they can attain
wealth, they can status,

00:27:33.620 --> 00:27:34.870 align:middle line:90%
they're going to have it made.

00:27:34.870 --> 00:27:36.786 align:middle line:84%
And so they're trying
